In the present day, web traffic holds the major segment of Internet-based traffic. This information can be retrieved by building a number of visits for a particular page by the number of callers which helps to know the popularity of the webpage. So predicting the web traffic for further can help to maintain unforeseen traffic load. In this project, we mainly pivot on forecasting the Wikipedia web traffic using Time series models techniques such as XXX. After comparing those models, we find the most suitable one which can be applied to this scenario.

Article names and metadata

We briefly separate the article information into data from wikipedia, wikimedia, and mediawiki due to the different formatting of the Page names. After that, we rejoin all article information into a common data set and name the object “tpages”.

tdates <- train %>% select(-Page)

foo <- train %>% select(Page) %>% rownames_to_column()
mediawiki <- foo %>% filter(str_detect(Page, "mediawiki"))
wikimedia <- foo %>% filter(str_detect(Page, "wikimedia"))
wikipedia <- foo %>% filter(str_detect(Page, "wikipedia")) %>% 
  filter(!str_detect(Page, "wikimedia")) %>%
  filter(!str_detect(Page, "mediawiki"))

wikipedia <- wikipedia %>%
  separate(Page, into = c("foo", "bar"), sep = ".wikipedia.org_") %>%
  separate(foo, into = c("article", "locale"), sep = -3) %>%
  separate(bar, into = c("access", "agent"), sep = "_") %>%
  mutate(locale = str_sub(locale,2,3))

wikimedia <- wikimedia %>%
  separate(Page, into = c("article", "bar"), sep = "_commons.wikimedia.org_") %>%
  separate(bar, into = c("access", "agent"), sep = "_") %>%
  add_column(locale = "wikmed")

mediawiki <- mediawiki %>%
  separate(Page, into = c("article", "bar"), sep = "_www.mediawiki.org_") %>%
  separate(bar, into = c("access", "agent"), sep = "_") %>%
  add_column(locale = "medwik")

tpages <- wikipedia %>%
  full_join(wikimedia, by = c("rowname", "article", "locale", "access", "agent")) %>%
  full_join(mediawiki, by = c("rowname", "article", "locale", "access", "agent"))

# tpages

    rownames_to_column %>% 
    filter(rowname == as.character(39460)) %>% 
    gather(dates, value, -rowname)%>% 
    spread(rowname, value) %>%
    mutate(dates = ymd(dates))%>%
    rename(views = as.character(39460))%>%
    rownames_to_column() %>%
    mutate(rowname = as.integer(rowname))
twitter <- ts(pageviews$views, frequency = 7)
twitter1 <- window(twitter, start = 67)
autoplot(twitter1) + xlab("weeks") + ylab("traffic") +
  ggtitle("traffic plot")

f1 <- forecast(ets(twitter1), h=126)
f2 <- snaive(twitter1, h=126)
f3 <- hw(twitter1, h=126, seasonal="multiplicative", damped=TRUE)
f4 <- hw(twitter1, h=126, seasonal="additive")
f5 <- hw(twitter1, h=126, seasonal="additive", damped=TRUE)

autoplot(twitter1) +
  autolayer(f1, PI=FALSE, series="ETS")+
  autolayer(f2, PI=FALSE, series="Snaive") +
  autolayer(f3, PI=FALSE, series="HW multiplicative Damped") +
  autolayer(f4, PI=FALSE, series="HW additive") +
  autolayer(f5, PI=FALSE, series="damped HW additive")  

arima.fit <- auto.arima(tsclean(twitter1),

                          d = 1, D = 1, stepwise = FALSE, approximation = FALSE)

fc_views <- arima.fit %>% forecast(h = 126, level = c(50,95))

pageviews <- tdates %>%
    rownames_to_column %>% 
    filter(rowname == as.character(51619)) %>% 
    gather(dates, value, -rowname)%>% 
    spread(rowname, value) %>%
    mutate(dates = ymd(dates))%>%
    rename(views = as.character(51619))%>%
    rownames_to_column() %>%
    mutate(rowname = as.integer(rowname))
Facebook <- ts(pageviews$views, frequency = 7)
Facebook1 <- window(Facebook, start = 67)
autoplot(Facebook1) + xlab("weeks") + ylab("traffic") +
  ggtitle("traffic plot")

f1 <- forecast(ets(Facebook1), h=126)
f2 <- snaive(Facebook1, h=126)
f3 <- hw(Facebook1, h=126, seasonal="multiplicative", damped=TRUE)
f4 <- hw(Facebook1, h=126, seasonal="additive")
f5 <- hw(Facebook1, h=126, seasonal="additive", damped=TRUE)
autoplot(Facebook1) +
  autolayer(f1, PI=FALSE, series="ETS")+
  autolayer(f2, PI=FALSE, series="Snaive") +
  autolayer(f3, PI=FALSE, series="HW multiplicative Damped") +
  autolayer(f4, PI=FALSE, series="HW additive") +
  autolayer(f5, PI=FALSE, series="damped HW additive")  

arima.fit <- auto.arima(tsclean(Facebook1),

                          d = 1, D = 1, stepwise = FALSE, approximation = FALSE)

fc_views <- arima.fit %>% forecast(h = 126, level = c(50,95))

autoplot(fc_views)

pred_len <- 60

  pred_range <- c(nrow(pageviews)-pred_len+1, nrow(pageviews))

  pre_views <- pageviews %>% head(nrow(pageviews)-pred_len)

  post_views <- pageviews %>% tail(pred_len)


  arima.fit <- auto.arima(tsclean(ts(pre_views$views, frequency = 7)),

                          d = 1, D = 1, stepwise = FALSE, approximation = FALSE)

  fc_views <- arima.fit %>% forecast(h = pred_len, level = c(50,95))

  autoplot(fc_views) +

    geom_line(aes(rowname/7, views), data = post_views, color = "grey40") +

    labs(x = "Time [weeks]", y = "views vs auto.arima predictions")
